21_0	0.8928571428571429	The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 8: &QL; &QL; The decline of the once-great salmon populations off the Pacific coasts of Canada and the United States ranks high on the list of the 20th century's environmental disasters.
21_1	0.0	But 1999 may well turn out to be the year when the fish finally caught a break.
21_2	1.8823529411764706	In March, acting under the Endangered Species Act, the federal government set in motion a regional plan to restore salmon runs throughout the Pacific Northwest.
21_3	0.65	Then last week, following years of fruitless negotiations, the United States and Canada announced a plan to set new limits on salmon catches and establish a conservation fund to further protect the fish.
21_4	0.11764705882352941	At the core of the complex agreement are new protections for ``intercepted'' salmon stocks _ fish that spawn in one country but are caught as they migrate through another country's waters.
21_5	0.11764705882352941	Under the old rules, fishermen in, say, Alaska or British Columbia were allowed to catch a fixed number of fish every year, regardless of the health of the fish population.
21_6	0.0	Under the new agreement, harvest levels would be adjusted up or down based on scientific measurements of fish stocks along thousands of miles of coastline.
21_7	0.05	The agreement also calls for a $140 million fund that would be used to buy up fishing licenses _ essentially paying some fishermen not to fish _ and to begin restoration efforts in rivers whose spawning areas have been damaged.
21_8	0.0	The importance of this agreement is that it finally addresses the demand side of the salmon equation.
21_9	0.0	The supply of fish can be increased if the rivers where they spawn are restored to good health.
21_10	0.0	But these efforts will mean little if the fish continue to be over-harvested at sea.
21_11	0.0	The agreement is also heartening in another sense.
21_12	0.0	As David Anderson, the Canadian fisheries minister, once observed, ``if two friendly neighbors can't agree on this issue, what does that forecast for diplomacy elsewhere''?
21_13	0.0	Anderson deserves much credit for this deal, along with Gov.
