23_1	0.10526315789473684	_ For roughly half of the millions of salmon born on the Snake River that set out each spring for the Pacific Ocean, the journey past four federal dams is an arduous and often lethal one.
23_2	0.0	They can be whacked to death by giant blades of the dam turbines, knocked out from collisions with concrete spillways, or succumb to a fatal condition not unlike the bends.
23_3	0.0	The other half of the salmon have a much simpler trip: They get to take the boat.
23_4	0.0	But this annual free ride, by which the U.S.
23_5	0.09090909090909091	Army Corps of Engineers loads the young fish on barges and totes them around the dams, is coming under scrutiny like never before.
23_6	0.18518518518518517	And for scientists, lawmakers, farmers, fishermen, American Indians, barge shippers, environmentalists and a breathtaking array of other interested parties, the assessment is most likely the key to a momentous decision that will ultimately fall to Congress: whether to take down the Snake River dams altogether.
23_7	0.0	The job of protecting the baby salmon, so they can mature and breed, is a remarkable feat of engineering and an expensive _ critics say outlandish _ accommodation to man's demands for electricity.
23_8	0.0	Thousands of fish a day are diverted to a channel leading to a pipe that runs into a trailer downstream of this dam, the first of the four, which is near the Idaho border.
23_9	0.0	In the trailer, a busy assembly line of seasonal workers briefly anesthetizes the salmon and then injects a computer chip the size of a rice grain into their bellies so they can be tracked over the years.
23_10	0.18181818181818182	They are barged for a 36-hour, 300-mile trip, bypassing the dams on the Snake and four more on the Columbia River.
23_11	0.0	More salmon are collected at two other dams on the Snake and one on the Columbia.
23_12	0.05555555555555555	It is all part of the government's bid to keep both salmon and dams _ ``to find a way to have our cake and eat it, too,'' said Jim Anderson, a fisheries professor at the University of Washington.
23_13	0.6206896551724138	But with the river's coho salmon already declared extinct, and every other species of Snake River salmon and steelhead now listed under the Endangered Species Act, the once-unthinkable idea of breaching the dams has emerged in several federal studies as the action with the best chance of restoring healthy salmon runs.
23_14	0.0	The Corps of Engineers is to recommend by the end of the year whether to propose such a step.
23_15	0.1111111111111111	Breaching of the dams is bitterly opposed by many people as an assault on the area's agricultural economy, and the proposal has already emerged as a hot-button issue in the Northwest in this year's presidential race.
23_16	0.0	Gov. George W.
23_17	0.0	Bush of Texas vowed in the primary campaign here never to allow the dams to be breached, while Vice President Al Gore, part of an administration that is intensely debating the issue, has taken no public position.
23_18	0.1111111111111111	Breaching the dams would mean removing the earthen portions, restoring a 140-mile section of the Snake to its wild, free-flowing condition and thus make salmon barging both impossible and unnecessary.
23_19	0.1111111111111111	It would also mean that the 4 percent of the electricity the dams provide in the Northwest would have to be supplied by other sources.
23_20	0.1	The cost of the 20-year-old barging program for juvenile salmon, known as smolts, is just part of the more than $3 billion the government has spent over that period trying to save salmon on the Snake and Columbia Rivers.
23_21	0.0	The barging program is derided by critics as a ``techno-fix'' that harms fish, interfering with their natural migration rhythms, causing them to die early, and perhaps interfering with their fabled and mysterious ability to find their way back home to spawn in their native river after spending years and traveling thousands of miles in the Pacific Ocean, as far north as Alaska.
23_22	0.1111111111111111	Supporters of barging defend it as a kind of magic solution that could allow the salmon and the dams to coexist.
23_23	0.0	(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) And the National Marine Fisheries Service, one of several federal agencies that must weigh in on the fate of the dams, recently said that a decision on breaching could be put off for 5 to 10 years if barging was continued and other aggressive conservation measures undertaken.
23_24	0.0	(END OPTIONAL TRIM) So far, however, the results are hardly encouraging.
23_25	0.0	While a corps brochure boasts that the barging system is ``custom-made to make the trip as safe and comfortable as possible,'' and while 98.5 percent of smolts survive the trip, the salmon themselves remain in decline.
